TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));

The solution of the linear system
\[
\begin{array}{rrrcr}
2x &+3y &-z &=& 14 \\
x &-y &-z&=& 0 \\
3x &+2y &-3z&=& 15 \\
\end{array}
\]
is 
$BR
\(x=\) \{ ans_rule(6) \},
EOT
ANS(num_cmp("2"));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
\(y=\) \{ ans_rule(6) \}, and
EOT
ANS(num_cmp("3"));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
\(z=\) \{ ans_rule(6) \}.

EOT
ANS(num_cmp("-1"));


SOLUTION(EV3(<<'EOT'));
$BR $BBOLD Solution:$EBOLD


\[
\begin{array}{lrrrrr}
\hbox{equation} & x & y & z & RHS & RS \\
{[1] } & 2 & 3 & -1 & 14 & 18 \\
{[2] } & 1 & -1 & -1 & 0 & -1 \\
{[3] } & 3 & 2 & -3 & 15 & 17 \\
{[4] =[2]-[1] } & -1 & -4 & 0 & -14 & -19 \\
{[5] = [3] - 3[1]  } & -3 & -7 & 0 & -27 & -37 \\
{[6]=[5]-3[4]  } & 0 & 5 & 0 & 15 & 20 \\
\end{array}
\]

The last equation, \(5y=15\) tells us that 
\(\underline{y=3}\). Substituting for \(y\) in equation \([4]\) gives
\(-x-12= -14\) or \(\underline{x=2}\). Substituting \(x\) and \(y\)
in equation \([2]\) gives  \(2-3-z=0\) or \(\underline{z=-1}\).

There are of course many alternative ways of solving this system.

EOT







